(Ford GoBike System Data Analysis)¶

by (Ahmed Nasr)¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This dataset includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area for the month of february,2019. The Dataset was provided by Udacity

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

  • The original raw dataset contains 183412 observations with 15 features. some variables are numerical and some are categorical. the wrangled dataset contains 174952 observations with 21 features.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  • Age groups of users
  • Genders
  • Average riding duration

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • I beilive the member age, gender, duration of use & user_type are the features of interset.

# Enhancing Gender distribution chart and add percentage for each gender 
# base_color = sb.set_theme(style="darkgrid")

base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
sb.countplot(data=df, y='member_gender', order=gender_order, color=base_color);
plt.ylabel('Gender', fontsize=14, labelpad=12)
plt.xlabel('Frequency %', fontsize=14, labelpad=12)
plt.title('Gender Distribution of Ford GoBike users', fontsize=16, y=1)

for i in range(gender_counts.shape[0]):
    # Gender_counts contains the frequency of unique values in the `member_gender` column in decreasing order.
    count = gender_counts[i]
    # Convert count into a percentage, and then into string
    pct_string = '{:0.1f}%'.format(100*count/n_df)
    # Print the string value on the bar. 
    plt.text(count+1, i, pct_string, va='center')
  • The percentage of male gender using the bike system is 74.2% , female 23.8%. & other 2%

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • The member age is right skewed distribution with average age of 34 years but it has unsual points, ages up to 141 years old
  • The hourly usage is bi-model distribution with peaks over two periods from 7-9 am & 4-6 pm.
  • The duration is right skewed distribution and observed some trip durations up to 23 hours while the avearge trip duration is 11 minutes

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

  • The member group age have outliers, it was removed from our data to focus of user group age from 18-min to 51-max
